{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_braniff_ver01/data/sn83045433/00294558111/1913121201/0155.xml":{"full_text":"5V-\"9BW\nr\nTHE WASHINGTON HERALD, EMDA, DECEMBER 12. 1913.\n,-&Kf) r'nry&!' ,\"T\"v5fl!r\nMARKETS, FINANCE, COMMERCE\nBYNEWHAVEN\nNew England Holders Sell\nStock, Owing to Loss of\nRegular Dividend.\nPENNSYLVANIAAFFECTED\nDemand for Capital Traction 5s on\nLocal 'Change Washington Rail\nway Common Advances.\nNew Haven's failure to declare a divi\ndend caused a bad break in the com\npany's stock on the New York Stock\nExchange yesterday. Pennsylvania nat\nurally -was influenced, also the latter\ndropping as low as 106 S-s from 108 1-8\nthough recovering and closinc at 107 WS\nNew Haven, which closed Wednesday\nmgnt at 72 3-4 fell as low as 67 3-8, clos\nings at 68 7-8. Suggestions of govern\nment ownership of telegraphs and tele\nphones from the Postmaster General\ncaused a cut in American Telephone and\nTelegraph to 115 3-4, the stock closing at\n117\nInterest largely was centered In the\nthree stocks, and the rest of the list re\nmained fairly steady.\nTrading In New Haen was unusually\nheavy. Fle thousand shares changed\nhands at prices that ranged from 63 to\n691-2. The maximum fall for the day\nwas 53-S.\nSelling orders appeared to come from\nall quarters and while shorts were large\nbuyers, brokers representing Philadelphia\nInterests took blocks of the stock around\nGS. This is believed to represent purchases\nfor the account of the Pennsylvania Rail\nroad who are credited with Increasing\ntheir holdings. In the later dealings floor\ntraders bid the stock up to 3. Technically\nthe stock Is oversold, and 11-16 premium\nwas demanded for the use of 100 shares\noer night.\nMnnrinnl Shnrea Up.\nV sharp upturn took place In the\nstandard shares. Steel common rose a\nfull point. Union crossed 153. Keadlng\ntouched 164 1-r; and Amalgamated Jumped\nI per cent on the turnover of I.0U0 shares\nThe passing of the Nev. Haven divi\ndend will have a far reaching effect that\ncould not possibly be discounted In one\nlay's trading. Half the stockholders are\nwomen, and many of the educational and\ncharitable institutions throughout New\nEngland relied upon dividends for their\nsupport.\nPennsvlvania, with its already large\nholdings, will buffer a temporary loss of\nincome. Pennsylvania stock fell to IMS\nAmerican Express, which owns something\nov er 50,000 shares of New Haven, dropped\nH- points.\nMany investors never disturb their\nholdings as long as dividends or interest\nis paid promptly. New England In\nvestors have leen hit by a series of inla\nnds enturcs that will no doubt compel\nthem to further liquidate their New\nHaven holdings\nThe principal difficulty about, the New\nHaven is that Its securities, temporarily\nat least, are put in a bad light, as Its\nbond, through regular dividends, have\nbeen eligible for Investments by savings\nbanks and trust funds\nChanges In the leading Issues were\nfractional Weakness was again noted\nIn man j of the less active issues. Amer\nican Tobacco lost 4 points- Pittsburgh.\nCincinnati, Chicago, and St Louis. 5.\nWestern Marjland. and Wells Kargo\nover 2 per cent. Rock Island 4s were\nweak In face of the declaration of the\nregular quarterly dividend on the old\nstock. Discussion of possible gov ernment\nownership broke Telephone 2 points, and\nWestern Union 1.\nClosing prices were generally firmer on\nshort covering\nLocal money market conditions showed\nlittle change.\nBrokers expressed the opinion that\nesterda s market gave a remarkable\ndemonstration of technical strength. At\ntention is called to the action of Read\ning. I'nlon Pacific and Steel The first\nis the favorite, with l nlon Pacific a\nclcrse second\nl.ocnl Mori KxchuiiKr.\nWhile the market for bonds on the\nlocal stock exchange jesterday was quiet,\nprices were maintained and the demand\nfor Capital Traction 5s was even better\nthan for th- last few dajs. live transac\ntions befng made at 1071-2.\nThe feature of the trading was In\nWashington Railway common, which,\nafter opening at Si 1-2, declined to S3, and\nlater advanced to SS. the trading amount\ning to 130 shares. After the regular call,\nrfowever, the stock was offered for sale\nat S7 1-2. without result.\nAnnouncement was made of the regular\ncruarterlv dividend of 12 per share on the\nstock of the Eastern Light and Fuel\nCompan\nIn the bank stock list sales were made\noh Federal National Bank at 133, and\nCommercial National Bank at 1S6\n'The prices were well maintained with\nthe possible exception of Metropolitan\nBank stock, which after sales at 190,\nclosed with a bid off 1SS a-S\nTen shares of Washington and Norfolk\nsteamboat were sold at 192.\nAfter call five shares of Mergenthalcr\nwent at 211.\nWhen compared with the situation\nexisting In other cities local financiers\ntake very favoraDle view or the dusi\nness \"being done b the local exchange.\nMuntx Actlnc Cnsliicr.\nRobert S. Stuntz. assistant cashier of\nthe Park Savings Bank, is acting cashier\nin place of E. F. Fawcett, resigned,\nTlnnk IZxmnlnera Appointed.\nThe Acting Comptroller of the Cur\nrency Kane, with the approval of Secre\ntary of the Treasury mcacioo. Jester\nday appointed Charles F RIddell, ol\nBrazil. Ind., a national bank examiner.\nHe will be assigned to duty in the Brazil\ndistrict in Indiana. Thomas E. Fletcher,\nof Forsyth, ua-, was appointed a na\ntlonal bank examiner for Southern Geor\ngia and Florida. Mr. RIddell served as\nSergeant-at-Arras of the House, under the\nlast administration.\nCOTTON STATISTICS.\nToday. Last\nyeas.\nVewTork. M\nNew Orleans....... 16.5W 13.080\nOalreaton........\". W7S 3!.E3\nMobile CT\nRaratmah SJ54 JB\nCuarieiton......... 2J6J 1.033\nWilmington..:, S.T5J IHJ\nNorfolk 3,9 130\nBaltimore\nBoston: 13 S\nVarious. 4S4 M.BT\nTotal.........!.... 4338 63 63\nINTEBIOK.\nHouston CJSn 15.28\nAngnats. 435 1JT9\nMemptda.j. T.r S-S\"\nJiCVM. ,334 8J40\nLKUe Koci....... V5t\ntoiti. Yn\nierday. 1X40 U40\n134 134\n1ZM 134